SL
()LN
EL
SL
(NAME)LN
EL
SL
(     CalcPot - calculate electrostatic potential)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(SYNOPSIS)LN
EL
SL
(     CalcPot expr expr expr expr expr expr)LN
EL
SL
(         expr \( zero | debye \) fileName)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(DESCRIPTION)LN
EL
SL
(     Calculate the electrostatic potential of all)LN
EL
SL
(     selected molecules, and write the result to a)LN
EL
SL
(     file with the given name. The resolution \(grid)LN
EL
SL
(     density\) depends on DrawPrec.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The first argument is the radius of the atoms, you)LN
EL
SL
(     will normally not change the default value 'vdw'.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The second argument determines the charge of the)LN
EL
SL
(     atoms, typical values are:)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(         charge: partial charges on all atoms)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(         heavycharge: partial charges of protons)LN
EL
SL
(             transferred to heavy atoms)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(         avgcharge: partial charges on heavy atoms,)LN
EL
SL
(             averaged over neighbours)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(         simplecharge: charges only on one or two atoms)LN
EL
SL
(             of charged residues, as specified in the)LN
EL
SL
(             setup file AtomCharges)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The third argument gives the dielectricity constant)LN
EL
SL
(     for the molecule, typically in the range 2 to 4, the)LN
EL
SL
(     fourth for the solvent, normally 80.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The fifth argument gives the solvent radius,)LN
EL
SL
(     normally 1.4 for water.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The sixth argument gives the salt concentration as)LN
EL
SL
(     ionic strength. For simple salts, this is twice the)LN
EL
SL
(     concentration, so the default value of 0.3)LN
EL
SL
(     corresponds to a salt concentration of 150 mMol.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The seventh argument gives the salt radius.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The eighth argument gives the size in Angstroms)LN
EL
SL
(     that \(on each side\) the box that the potential is)LN
EL
SL
(     calculated in is larger than the extent of the)LN
EL
SL
(     molecule. Values of 10 to 15 are recommended.)LN
EL
SL
(     Smaller values reduce the calculation time, but may)LN
EL
SL
(     introduce artifacts from the boundary conditions.)LN
EL
SL
()LN
EL
SL
(     The ninth argument selects the kind of boundary)LN
EL
SL
(     condition, either values fixed at zero, or)LN
EL
SL
(     Debye-Hueckel. Using zero is faster, and there)LN
EL
SL
(     does not seem to be a noticable difference between)LN
EL
